Written evidence submitted by the Equality and Human Rights Commission (JRR 0032)default&#xa0;defaultIntroduction defaultThe Equality and Human Rights Commission (
default‘
defaultthe Commission
default’
default) welcomes the opportunity of responding to the Joint Committee on Human Rights 
default(JCHR) inquiry into the implications for access to justice of the Government
default’
defaults proposed judicial review reforms.  Because of o
defaultur statutory remit under the Equality Act 2006 and our status as a National Human Rights Institution, t
defaulthe focus of this inquiry is
default highly relevant to our work.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe 
defaultMinistry of Justice (MoJ), describes judicial review as 
default‘
defaulta critical check on the power of the state, providing an effective mechanism for challenging the decisions, acts or omissions of public bodies to ensure that they a
defaultre lawful
default’
default.
default   
defaultJudicial review is the principal means of testing the compatibility of administrative decisions with rights under the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR).  In relation to civil rights and obligations, where an internal complaints proc
defaultedure does not qualify as an 
default‘
defaultindependent and impartial tribunal
default’
default 
defaultunder Article 6(1) of the ECHR, judicial review may provide the independent scrutiny that is required by the Convention. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Commission has submitted a detailed response to the MoJ consult
defaultation on the proposed judicial review reforms; this response forms the basis of our submission to the JCHR inquiry.  In summary, the Commission
default’
defaults assessment of the MoJ
default’
defaults proposals is that they would have a substantial adverse impact on the ability of indiv
defaultiduals and organisations to hold the state to account, including in relation to potentia
defaultl human rights breaches.  They 
defaultwould also potentially restrict access to justice for certain cases that involve rights under the Equality Act 2010, including the public
default sector equality duty (PSED) under section 149 of that Act.  
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the Commission
default’
defaults assessment, the MoJ has not provided adequate evidence in support of its proposals. The number of judicial review applications (excluding immigration and asylum) has remaine
defaultd almost 
defaultstable since 2007.
default   Our own experience of judicial review litigation suggests that the proposals, if implemented, will deliver limited costs savings but will run the risk of causing delays in the court process and create extra costs which outwei
defaultgh the perceived benefits.  
default&#xa0;
defaultWe note that the MoJ does not collect comprehensive information on the protected characteristics of court users generally, or specifically those involved in judicial review proceedings.  As the consultation paper acknowledges,
default this limits the Government
default’
defaults understanding of the potential equality impacts of its proposals, including those for legal aid.  To gain better understanding of the equality impact of any judicial review reforms, we recommend that steps are taken undertake 
defaultproportionate monitoring of court users by reference to relevant protected characteristics, including by drawing on existing data sources. In the Commission
default’
defaults analysis, it is particularly important to monitor the equalities impact of any proposals for reso
defaultlving disputes involving the PSED.  
defaultEvidence of differential experiences of the civil justice system is available from the Commission
default’
defaults Measurement Framework (MF).
default  The MF is designed to monitor a set of indicators and measures across 11 
default‘
defaultdomains
default’
default, including legal security. Within this domain, Indicator 4 relates to equal protection and support for individuals with justiciable civil justice problems. Evidence within this indicator indicates differences in the advice-seeking behaviour of people who 
defaultshare protected characteristics when faced by civil law problems. For example, people aged 18 to 24 and those aged 75 and over; people who are Asian, Black, mixed race or Chinese; and Buddhists and Hindus are less likely than other groups to obtain advice 
defaultwhen faced with a civil justice problem.
default 
defaultThe test for standing defaultThe MoJ proposes introducing a more restricted test for 
default‘
defaultstanding
default’
default, which would limit the individuals and organisations that could bring claims for judicial review.  For the reasons outlined 
defaultbelow, the Commission does not consider that any change to the test is required.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Impact Assessment published alongside the MoJ consultation paper has not monetised the impacts of this proposal, merely stating that the Government is 
default‘
defaultconcerned
default’
default 
defaultthat over time the courts have given an increasingly generous interpretation of the current 
default‘
defaultsufficient interest
default’
default 
defaulttest for standing.    
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Commission regularly monitors judicial review claims involving equality and/or human rights issues and has extens
defaultive experience of intervening in such claims. We are not aware of claims being allowed to proceed where the claimant has had little or no interest in the matter or where judicial review is being used as a mere campaigning tool, beyond what is reasonably th
defaulte concern of an interested party.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn our assessment, the current standing test is fit for purpose, and a narrower test may have a negative impact on pre-hearing costs and on court time. The existing rules have been set out clearly by the courts
default and these
default rules already exclude judicial reviews by people with little or no interest in the claim.   
default&#xa0;
defaultAs recently acknowledged by the Right Hon Lady Justice Hale,
default public law is concerned with public wrongs, rather than individual rights. A broad test for standin
defaultg allows alleged abuses of executive power to be challenged when those affected by a policy or decision cannot bring a case themselves 
default–
default 
defaultfor logistical or financial reasons, because they are not aware of the issue, or because they lack access to lawyers.  
defaultThe Commission's analysis suggests that many public interest challenges could not otherwise be brought by a claimant with a direct personal interest in the matter. 
default&#xa0;
defaultFor example, there is sometimes no victim who could, in practice, bring a claim.  This is 
defaultillustrated by the judicial review in which Medical Justice, a non-governmental organisation (NGO), successfully challenged a policy that certain individuals would get little or no notice of their removal directions (the specific arrangements made for thei
defaultr removal from the United Kingdom). No individual could have brought 
defaultthat claim because by the time they became aware that the policy applied to them they would be in the process of being deported.
default  
defaultIt may also sometimes be appropriate for a judicial rev
defaultiew application to be made before new legislation takes effect.  In these circumstances, an organisation is more likely to bring the claim, because the legislation has not yet had a direct impact on any individuals.  One example is the judicial review brou
defaultght by Age UK
default challenging the national default retirement age of 65 that was about to be introduced by the Employment Equality (Age) Regulations 2006. 
defaultThese examples illustrate the important role of NGOs in relation to issues where there is no appropriat
defaulte individual who can bring the claim, although the volume of cases that they bring is acknowledged by the MoJ to be relatively small.
default  NGOs are often well placed to represent the interests of an affected group, can support their claim with specialist evid
defaultence, and their presence lends an institutional overview to the issue.  Considering a claim on a question of policy or legal principle brought by an NGO is a more efficient use of court time than dealing with a group claim brought by many different individ
defaultuals.  In these circumstances, it is also more appropriate for the court not to be limited to considering the facts of individual cases.
default&#xa0;
defaultSimilarly, the court has been willing to accept the standing of professional representative groups, when the interest
defaults of their members are affected rather than the interests of the group itself.
default  In a few cases, the court has shown itself willing to recognise the standing of a concerned individual bringing a public interest challenge.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultUnder Section 30 Equality Act 2
default006, the Commission has standing to apply for judicial review in relation to its statutory functions. We have 
defaultmade reference to this power in pre-action correspondence where litigation was ultimately avoided.  In a small number of cases, and only after ext
defaultensive engagement with the public body concerned, we have used Section 30 to issue proceedings where we considered that it was in the public interest for us to act to avoid the risk of a breach of equality or human rights law that could not be addressed by
default other means.  One example is the case of R (Equality and Human Rights Commission) v Secretary of State for Justice,
default  where the Commission argued successfully that the National Offender Management Service had failed to comply with the Race Equality Duty o
defaultr the Disability Equality Duty in concluding a service level agreement with the UK Border Agency for the removal of foreign national prisoners.  
default&#xa0;
defaultResearch indicates that a high proportion of judicial review claims settle in favour
default of the claimant, suggesting that the majority of cases have substantial merit.
default Our own experience as an intervener in judicial review cases confirms that settlements favourable to the claimant are often reached before the final hearing.  
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the Commiss
defaultion
default’
defaults assessment, none of the alternative tests for standing suggested by the MoJ in its consultation paper would be appropriate.  The standing test for challenges to EU measures in the European Court of Justice is too narrow, and would not sit well with t
defaulthe UK traditions of open access to justice. The narrow 
default‘
defaultvictim
default’
default 
defaulttest under the HRA has proved to be a barrier to a number of public interest challenges, and this problem would only be compounded if the test were introduced for ordinary public law claims.  
defaultWhile the tests for statutory planning challenges (
default‘
defaulta person aggrieved
default’
default) and for civil legal aid are both preferable to either the EU or HRA test, our assessment is that the current, well-established test is more appropriate than either of these. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe MoJ
default has not considered the possibility that introducing a narrower test for standing could lead to an increase in pre-hearing costs to resolve disputes.  Requiring judicial interpretation of a new standing test may 
defaultcause additional court time and resources to
default be spent on satellite litigation.  Another factor that has not been considered is the possibility that preventing NGOs and representative bodies from bringing individual claims could lead to an increase in group claims 
default–
default 
defaultthat is, where individual claimant
defaults raising similar issues apply to the court for a Group Litigation Order.  This would undoubtedly lead to more costly and resource intensive litigation for both claimants and defendants and an increase in the burden on the courts.  
default&#xa0;
defaultAs the MoJ recognises,
default standing cannot be restricted in environmental law cases because of the requirements of the Aarhus Convention.
default  In the Commission
default’
defaults analysis, there is no principled distinction between environmental challenges and challenges involving equality and human 
defaultrights issues. There is also a risk that changing the standing test for non-environmental cases would create satellite litigation to establish whether a particular issue is 
default‘
defaultenvironmental
default’
default 
defaultor not. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThird party interventions defaultThe role of an intervener is t
defaulto assist the court with relevant evidence or information, submissions of law, expertise or a perspective which has not already been provided by the parties (and so would not otherwise be available to the Court). An intervener does not become a party to the
default proceedings and do
defaultes
default not necessarily align with either party or have a personal interest in the outcome of the case. There is no right of intervention and the Court determines whether leave to intervene is given, usually only where it considers the interv
defaultention will be necessary or helpful.
default default In the Commission's own experience of making interventions, the process by which a prospective intervener applies for leave to intervene
default defaultprovides a level of scrutiny which ensures clarity about the nature and value of
default an intervention. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe application process also assists in quantifying the likely costs arising from a proposed intervention. The parties have an opportunity to give their views to the court with regard to the merits of the application to intervene, the form/means of the int
defaultervention (oral or written) and the 
defaulttiming of it, together with the costs implications. Interveners are not invariably granted leave to make oral submissions to the court. Where the court does grant permission to make an oral submission, this is often limi
defaultted to no more than an hour 
default–
default 
defaultor in some cases to 20 minutes. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe additional material provided by interveners can play an important role in judicial review proceedings, owing to their adversarial nature. The parties may not have the time, resources or ex
defaultpertise to provide all the information relevant to determining the issues, especially where questions of public importance arise and the impact of the judgment extends beyond the facts of the case.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe value of interventions was considered by the Right 
defaultHon Baroness Hale, Deputy President of the Supreme Court, in a recent speech.
default Her view was that the court often welcomes help on difficult issues and that permission is given to interveners because the court wants to have a broader perspective of the issu
defaultes before it because, in an adversarial system, the parties cannot be relied on in this regard.  She suggested that it can be particularly helpful when an intervener makes submissions in relation to international jurisprudence and instruments.  In her view
default, there was often value in allowing oral submissions, as this gives an intervener the chance to react to the court and answer specific questions which the court may wish to raise. 
default&#xa0;
defaultStatistics about the number and nature of interveners are not currently co
defaultllated by HM Courts and Tribunals Service (HMCTS) but a report by the NGO Justice
default found that there were 89 interveners in the House of Lords between 2005 and 2009. Of these, 44 were public bodies (including government departments), 34 were NGOs and 11 wer
defaulte private organisations. Taking account of the high proportion of interveners that are public bodies, it is clear that intervening in proceedings is a legal tool which they value, often as a means of supporting their own interpretation of law or policy.  
default&#xa0;
defaultSince 2007, the Commission has intervened in 27 cases in the administrative court, of which 22 have been concluded and four have only recently been heard or are awaiting hearing.  Our assessment is 
defaultthat in 14 of those 22 cases, the Commission
default’
defaults interventi
defaulton has had a substantial influence on the proceedings. This includes instances where the court has reflected and/or adopted the Commission's submissions in its judgment 
default–
default 
defaultirrespective of whether or not there was a successful outcome for the claimant. It al
defaultso includes cases where, in the Commission
default’
defaults assessment, 
defaultour
default intervention has encouraged settlement. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn some cases, the Commission has been asked to intervene by the court. One example is the case of A Local Authority v A (a child) &amp; Anor,
default where the Commission
default’
defaults submissions on the positive obligations under Article 5 ECHR were accepted by the court. In 
defaultR (South West Care Homes &amp; Others) v Devon County Council
default,
default the Commission intervened to clarify the relevance of the PSED for authorities w
defaulthen they are developing proposals.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Commission
default’
defaults submissions contributed to the final ruling, with the court emphasising the need for authorities to give due regard to the potential impact on vulnerable people of possible care home closures or reduced s
defaultupport.
default default&#xa0;defaultBased on our analysis of the role of interveners outlined above, and our own experience of making interventions, the Commission supports the proposal for a presumption that interveners bear their own costs 
default–
default 
defaultbut not the costs incurred by the clai
defaultmant or defendant when pursuing issues raised by the intervener.  It is our own practice, when applying to intervene, to state that we will be responsible for our own costs.  
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, there may be cases where an intervener takes a more central role in pr
defaultoceedings. For example, in R (E) v Governing Body of Jewish Free School &amp; others,
default costs were awarded against one of the interveners, the United Synagogue, which had taken a principal role in opposing the claim. In circumstances such as these, the court ha
defaults discretion to consider making an award of costs against an intervener, using the approach set out in Rule 46(3) and Practice Direction 6.9 of 
defaultthe Rules of the Supreme Court.
default  There may also be situations where, under the court rules, a party could pursu
defaulte a wasted costs order.
